 for bestpractices and # Password Management & Reset

## Overview
Build secure, user-friendly password management and reset functionality for Archject. This includes a User Profile page where authenticated users can change their password and manage 2FA/connected apps, and a Password Reset flow (request and reset) that uses one-time, time-limited tokenized links delivered by email. Implement robust backend APIs, token hashing, rate limiting, email templates, input validation, and audit logging consistent with Archject’s security posture and visual design system.

## Components to Build
1. Password Reset Request API and page
   - Frontend: Password Reset Request page (page_password_reset) with email input, validation, and feedback states.
   - Backend: POST /auth/password-reset-request to accept an email and send a tokenized reset link if the account exists. Enforce rate limiting and generic responses to prevent user enumeration.
   - Email: HTML + plain-text reset email template that includes secure link with token parameter.

2. Password Reset Submit API and page
   - Frontend: Password Reset page reachable via link with token param; accepts new password + confirm, runs client-side validation, and submits token + password to backend.
   - Backend: POST /auth/password-reset to verify token, set new password, invalidate token (one-time use), explode sessions as configured, log the change, and optionally notify the user.

3. Change Password within User Profile
   - Frontend: Profile page section allowing authenticated users to change password by entering current password, new password, confirm new password. For critical operations require re-authentication or current-password confirmation.
   - Backend: Endpoint (PUT /user/password or POST /user/change-password) that checks current password, applies password policy, updates credentials, invalidates sessions/tokens as needed, and logs event.

4. Token storage & management
   - Backend: DB model to store password reset tokens (hashed), expiration timestamps, usage flag, IP and user-agent metadata for audit, plus background cleanup.

5. Rate limiting & abuse protection
   - Backend & infra: Rate limit per IP and per account for password-reset-request and password-reset submit endpoints, exponential backoff or CAPTCHAs if thresholds exceeded.

6. Security & auditing
   - Backend: One-time-use hashed tokens, strong randomness (e.g., 32+ bytes base64 or URL-safe), short expiration (default 1 hour), log events (request, email delivered, token used, password changed).
   - Email notifications on password change (if not via reset) and optionally when reset occurs.

7. Tests & monitoring
   - Unit tests for token lifecycle, password policy, endpoint behaviors.
   - Integration tests for end-to-end flow (request -> email generation -> reset).
   - Logging hooks and metrics for rate-limit events and reset attempts.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages & components:
  - Password Reset Request Page (public, unauthenticated)
    - Layout card centered in a constrained form container (per design system).
    - Elements: H2 "Reset your password", description text, email input, primary button "Send reset link" (accent #0052CC), secondary "Back to sign in".
    - States: idle, loading, success (generic message), error (generic for rate-limited or server errors).
    - UX: After submit show success copy regardless of account existence: "If an account exists for this email, we sent a link. Check your inbox." Include CTA to contact support if not received.
    - Validation: client-side email format validation; throttle click actions.

  - Password Reset Page (public, via token link)
    - URL: /password-reset?token=...
    - Layout: same card; H2 "Create a new password".
    - Fields: new password, confirm password, strength meter, show/hide toggle, reminders about password policy.
    - Auto-check: on page load optionally POST /auth/password-reset-validate (or the POST /auth/password-reset will validate token) to show "Invalid or expired link" view before form.
    - Interactions: submit disabled until password/confirm valid and strength acceptable; upon success redirect to sign-in with success toast or to profile if auto-signed-in.
    - Error handling: expired/invalid token message with link to re-request reset.

  - User Profile Page (authenticated)
    - Section: "Security" card containing:
      - Change password form: fields current password, new password, confirm new password, primary button "Update password".
      - 2FA management area (placeholder in scope): toggle enable/disable, manage devices (UI hooks but implement only the skeleton if 2FA out of scope).
      - Connected apps section: list of OAuth/connected apps with revoke buttons.
      - Visual alignment and spacing per design system (cards, borders, typography).
    - Behavior: require entering current password; show loader and success / error messages; on success show brief success pill and send password-change notification email.

- Visual & behavior specifics:
  - Use color palette and typography as given.
  - Buttons: primary #0052CC with white text; disabled state muted.
  - Inputs: rounded with #D1D5DB borders, focus ring using accent with subtle shadow.
  - Password strength meter: three-tier bars with labels (Weak/Medium/Strong), color usage: Weak = #EF4444, Medium = #F59E42, Strong = #10B981.
  - Accessibility: labels with for attribute, aria-live regions for async messages, proper contrast, keyboard-accessible.
  - Microcopy: concise, non-judgmental, avoid account enumeration.

- Frontend Tech Notes:
  - Use current UI component library (React + design system components).
  - Centralized form validation using schema (Yup/Zod).
  - Use client-side rate-limit UX: disable button for N seconds after click and show countdown when backend signals rate-limit.

### Backend
- Stack assumptions: Node.js (Express/Fastify/Nest), PostgreSQL (or relational DB), ORMs supported (Prisma/TypeORM/Sequelize). Adapt schema names to current project conventions.

- Database models:
  - users (existing): id (uuid), email (unique, indexed), password_hash, last_password_changed_at, sessions metadata etc.
  - password_reset_tokens (new): id (uuid), user_id (FK users.id, nullable to allow storing requests without account? prefer non-null), token_hash (varchar), created_at (timestamp), expires_at (timestamp), used_at (timestamp nullable), request_ip, request_user_agent.
  - password_reset_rate_limits (optional): id, ip_or_account_key, attempts, window_start, block_until.
  - audit_logs (existing or new): event_type (PASSWORD_RESET_REQUEST, PASSWORD_RESET_COMPLETED, PASSWORD_CHANGED), user_id (nullable), ip, user_agent, metadata JSON, timestamp.

- APIs to implement:
  - POST /auth/password-reset-request
    - Request body: { email: string }
    - Behavior:
      - Rate limit by IP and email (e.g., 5 requests per hour per IP, 3 per hour per account).
      - If user exists:
        - Generate secure random token (crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex') or base64url), hash token with bcrypt/sha256+pepper and store token_hash with expires_at = now + 1 hour, used_at = null, metadata.
        - Send email with link: https://app.archject.com/password-reset?token=<raw token>&email=<url-encoded email> (email param optional; token alone acceptable).
      - Respond with 200 and generic message regardless of existence.
      - Log event (do not include token in logs).
    - Security:
      - Throttle and generic success message.
      - Do not reveal whether account exists.

  - POST /auth/password-reset
    - Request body: { token: string, password: string, email?: string }
    - Behavior:
      - Validate token: hash received token same way as stored; find token record where token_hash matches and used_at is null and expires_at > now.
      - Optional: match by user and email for added safety.
      - If valid:
        - Validate password against policy (see below).
        - Update users.password_hash (use Argon2 or bcrypt with current work factor), set last_password_changed_at = now.
        - Mark token.used_at = now.
        - Invalidate all other active sessions / API tokens (or provide option to keep current session).
        - Emit audit log and send notification email "Your password was changed".
        - Return 200 with success.
      - If invalid or expired: return 400 with generic "Invalid or expired token" message.
      - Rate limit attempts per token and per IP to mitigate brute-force.

  - PUT /user/password or POST /user/change-password
    - Authenticated endpoint.
    - Request body: { currentPassword: string, newPassword: string }
    - Behavior:
      - Verify currentPassword matches stored hash.
      - Validate new password.
      - Update the password hash, set last_password_changed_at.
      - Invalidate sessions/tokens as policy requires.
      - Return 200, send notification email.

  - Optional GET /auth/password-reset-validate
    - Query: token
    - Return 200 if token valid else 400. Use to provide immediate UX feedback on opening reset page.

- Token management details:
  - Store only token_hash (sha256(token + serverPepper) or bcrypt), never the raw token.
  - Token length: 32+ bytes of entropy.
  - Expire tokens after 60 minutes by default; allow admin configuration.
  - One-time use: set used_at when consumed; queries should filter used_at is null.

- Email integration:
  - Use project's email service (SendGrid/Mailgun/Postmark).
  - Template: branded header with Archject logo, clear CTA button with reset link, expiration text, and safety tips if email wasn't requested.
  - Track send attempts and log delivery events.

- Rate limiting & abuse:
  - Implement middleware or gateway-level rate limiting for:
    - POST /auth/password-reset-request: per IP and per email.
    - POST /auth/password-reset: per IP and per token.
  - On repeated abuse, block further attempts and surface support contact.

- Logging & monitoring:
  - Audit events for password reset request (anonymized if user not found), password change success/failure, token use, and rate-limit triggers.
  - Expose metrics for reset requests, successes, failures, and rate limits.

### Integration
- Connection flow:
  - Frontend calls POST /auth/password-reset-request -> backend validates rate limits, persists hashed token, dispatches email.
  - User receives email -> clicks link -> frontend loads /password-reset?token=... -> frontend optionally validates token via GET /auth/password-reset-validate -> user submits new password -> frontend calls POST /auth/password-reset -> backend validates token, updates password, invalidates token & sessions, logs, and responds.
  - When authenticated user changes password in profile -> frontend calls PUT /user/password -> backend verifies current password and updates it; backend sends alert email and invalidates sessions.
- Notifications:
  - Email templates used for both reset link and password changed confirmations.
- Session handling:
  - On password change via reset, optionally sign the user in (if secure) or redirect to login and force re-authentication. Default: redirect to sign-in to avoid token reuse and enforce MFA if enabled.
- 2FA considerations:
  - If user has 2FA enabled, require re-enrollment/re-check after password reset (or at minimum require 2FA on next sign-in). Document behavior and update user profile UI accordingly.

## User Experience Flow
1. User forgets password -> clicks "Forgot password" on sign-in.
2. User lands on Password Reset Request page, enters email, clicks "Send reset link".
3. Frontend shows generic success message: "If an account exists for this email, we sent a link."
4. User receives email with link containing token and clicks it.
5. The link opens Password Reset Page:
   - If token invalid/expired: show friendly message and "Resend reset link".
   - If token valid: show new-password form with strength meter.
6. User enters and confirms new password, click "Set new password".
7. Backend validates token and password, updates password, marks token used, invalidates sessions, logs events, sends email "Your password was changed".
8. Frontend shows success and redirects user to sign-in, optionally with a prompt to re-enable 2FA if needed.
9. Authenticated users can change password from Profile page by entering current password and the new password; on success receive email and see in-app confirmation.

## Technical Specifications
- Data Models:
  - users (existing fields highlighted)
    - id: uuid (PK)
    - email: varchar, unique, indexed
    - password_hash: varchar
    - last_password_changed_at: timestamp
    - mfa_enabled: boolean
  - password_reset_tokens
    - id: uuid PK
    - user_id: uuid FK -> users.id (not null)
    - token_hash: varchar (sha256 hex or bcrypt)
    - created_at: timestamptz default now()
    - expires_at: timestamptz
    - used_at: timestamptz nullable
    - request_ip: inet or varchar
    - request_user_agent: text
  - audit_logs (if not existing)
    - id, event_type, user_id, ip, user_agent, metadata jsonb, created_at

- API Endpoints:
  - POST /auth/password-reset-request
    - Body: { email: string }
    - Responses: 200 { message } (generic), 429 rate limited
  - POST /auth/password-reset
    - Body: { token: string, password: string, email?: string }
    - Responses: 200 success, 400 invalid/expired, 429 rate limited
  - GET /auth/password-reset-validate?token=...
    - Responses: 200 valid info, 400 invalid/expired
  - PUT /user/password (auth required)
    - Body: { currentPassword: string, newPassword: string }
    - Responses: 200 success, 400 invalid current, 422 validation errors
  - Optional: GET /user/profile (for view)

- Security:
  - Authentication: endpoints that modify password require proper auth (change-password), resets rely on token and rate limiting.
  - Tokenization: use high-entropy tokens; store only token_hash (use sha256(token + serverPepper) or bcrypt); raw token must be delivered only via secure email link with HTTPS.
  - HTTPS required everywhere; links must be absolute and include domain config.
  - One-time use tokens; short expiration (60 minutes).
  - Rate limiting: per IP & per account.
  - Session invalidation: invalidate existing sessions on password change (with option to keep current), rotate refresh tokens.
  - Brute-force mitigation: limit attempts for token submission; log and alert abnormal patterns.
  - Avoid user enumeration: always return generic responses for reset requests.
  - Email contents: do not include raw password or token in logs; include support contact.
  - Re-auth requirement: for critical profile updates, require current password or 2FA.

- Validation:
  - Email: RFC-compliant format check and normalized lowercase.
  - Password policy (server & client):
    - Minimum 12 characters
    - At least one uppercase, one lowercase, one number, and one symbol OR require passphrase with minimum entropy; prefer NIST guidance (allow long passphrases)
    - Disallow common passwords via a banned list (top 100k) and deny substrings of user's email or name.
    - Confirm password must match.
  - Token: required, URL-safe characters only.
  - Rate-limit headers: include Retry-After on 429.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] POST /auth/password-reset-request returns 200 generic message and, if account exists, stores a hashed token with expires_at and sends an email containing a secure reset link.
- [ ] Reset link token is one-time use and expires after configured TTL (default 1 hour). Used tokens are marked used and cannot be reused.
- [ ] POST /auth/password-reset validates token and password, updates the user password hash, invalidates sessions, sends password-changed notification email, and returns success only for valid tokens.
- [ ] Password change in User Profile requires current password, validates new password policy, updates password, invalidates sessions as configured, and sends notification.
- [ ] Rate limiting prevents abuse (configurable thresholds) and endpoints return 429 with Retry-After when limits are exceeded.
- [ ] UI pages follow the provided visual style, show appropriate success/error states, and do not reveal whether a given email exists.
- [ ] Unit and integration tests cover token creation, expiration, reuse prevention, password validation, and rate limit behavior.
- [ ] Audit logs capture reset request, token usage, password change events with IP and user-agent metadata.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Pages use 12-column grid, centered form cards with 24–32px spacing.
- Typography scales: H2 ~22px for card headings, body 15–16px.
- Buttons: primary (#0052CC), secondary ghost style.
- Inputs: rounded, light gray borders (#D1D5DB), focus ring using accent.
- Cards: white background (#FFFFFF), subtle shadow, 8–12px border-radius.
- Password strength meter colors: Weak #EF4444, Medium #F59E42, Strong #10B981.
- Messaging tone: professional, calm, and helpful; always use non-enumerative copy for reset request responses.
- Accessibility: semantic HTML, ARIA where needed, keyboard focus flows, color contrast meeting WCAG AA.

Design details to include in delivery:
- Mockups for:
  - Password Reset Request page (idle/success/error)
  - Password Reset page (valid token/new password, invalid token)
  - Profile Security card with Change Password form (success/error)
- Include copy strings for email templates, button text, and in-app success/error messages.

